    "posts": [
      {
        "id": 3051819,
        "name": "Blake Brown",
        "username": "Blake_Brown",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/blake_brown/{size}/1195_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-12-20T19:32:30.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Often I am reminded of the age old discussion about some of the new world Pinot Noir being likened to red Burgundy and I understand the intent to replicate such fabulous wines that have served the test of time and truly are a superior expression of this Vitis vinifera star among stars; when first exploring these 2 wines, there was no doubt about their place of origin; I think I\u2019d get this 10 out of 10 times in a blind tasting.  Famous last words as I`ve been humbled numerous times in blind formats.  I might not get their communes, but for sure  that they are of Premier Cru quality if not Grand Cru.</p>\n<p>So what are the characteristics that lead me to these conclusions?  Richness, acidity, balance, depth and complexity, concentration, power and finesse, texture, generally a more darker fruit profile and lots more.  I have found many new world Pinots have some or most of these characteristics, but there\u2019s still just a sense of place that comes off and these 2 wines are pure Burgundy.</p>\n<p>2013 DOMAINE JOSEPH ROTY les FONTENYS GEVREY-CHAMBERTIN 1er Cru- decanted an hour ahead of serving; the intense pure ruby color denotes something serious is coming and the nose gives the first testament with full on spicy and cinnamon accented red and dark fruit which on the palate translates into ripe red raspberry, red cherry, blackberry, black cherry and even a touch of cranberry fruit that continues on while being delivered to the back end in a rich and super smooth medium; it\u2019s seamless and perfectly in harmony throughout; the tannins are tame and nicely integrated making it very soft and easy on the palate; the oak influence is also ideally integrated and it\u2019s just in such a good place now and one can count on this sharing its love for many years to come.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/uploads/db3686/original/3X/e/b/eb71b9122e432bda2d197f4f8c25798c233f6e5f.jpeg\" alt=\"IMG_0073.jpeg\" data-base62-sha1=\"xAPR3LcxZnow7VtVJaVtNpq6gJF\" width=\"2110\" height=\"4032\"><br>\n2013 LUCIEN LE MOINE les VAUCRAINS NUITS ST. GEORGES 1er Cru- decanted for over an hour prior to pouring; it had a youthful red purple color; as with the 13<code> Roty Fonteny</code>s, it was another spectacular reminder of how wondrous red Burgs are as if I needed to be reminded for over 20+ years of fond appreciation; the aromatics included cinnamon and spice laden red and dark fruit which on the palate revealed raspberry, red plum, blackberry and blueberry; its full bodied with a super smooth and silky mouthfeel; the finish seemed to highlight the cinnamon and spice accented raspberry as the last wonderful impression.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/uploads/db3686/original/3X/0/6/06a3e1f8f3f8f0e8cb9e51117a5b82157a75d5f0.jpeg\" alt=\"IMG_0078.jpeg\" data-base62-sha1=\"WJYSpY0Y27GuEo2qLcr64iJhqE\" width=\"4032\" height=\"3024\"><br>\nI\u2019ve had my cinnamon and spicy red raspberry fix to see me through the holidays.  Well maybe not quite yet as there is a 97` Williams Selyem Precious Mountain red Burg like Pinot coming up later today.</p>\n<p>Cheers,<br>\nBlake</p>",
